Literal translation of the opening kasha: A literal (but unclear) translation of the opening kasha is:
> "Now that with his agent he is mekadesh, with himself is needed."
Questions on this translation might include: [[What is 'with his agent he is mekadesh' referring to?]] [[What is 'with himself' refering to?]] and [[What does "is needed" mean here?]]

What is 'with his agent he is mekadesh' referring to? You might wonder what the words "with his agent he can mekadesh" are referring to. They are a reference to the Mishna, which said that a man can be mekadesh with his agent.

What is 'with himself' refering to? You might ask what does the word "with himself" mean in the sentence "with himself is needed". "With himself" is a quotation from the Mishna, and so the subject of the sentence is the word "בו", and the literal translation of the Gemara is that it is saying "the word בו in the Mishna is needed".

What does "is needed" mean here? The Gemara uses the phrase "is needed" (coming from [[the shoresh בעה]]) to speak about words in the Mishna and why each one is needed. It is a basic assumption of the Gemara that every word of the Mishna is necessary, and so if we find a word that teaches something we can infer from another word, the Gemara will ask why it is needed.

Pshat in the opening kasha: The opening kasha seems to be asking: now that the Mishna has taught us that a man can be mekadesh via his agent, then I already know by implication that the lesser chiddush that he can be mekadesh himself is true, so why did the Mishna have to teach it to me?

Ha'aras on the opening kasha: From the opening kasha, we see certain assumptions the Gemara is making about the Mishna.

Two lishnas of the Gemara's terutz: After the opening kasha, the Gemara gives a [[first lishna]], and a [[second lishna]]. ([["Lishna"|What is a "lishna"?]])

First lishna: The first lishna is an answer to the Gemara's kasha, quoted below. The first lishna is composed of the [[amira of R Yosef]] and [[ha d'Rav Safra]].
> [גמ' השתא בשלוחו מקדש בו מיבעיא] אמר
> רב יוסף מצוה בו יותר מבשלוחו כי הא דרב
> ספרא מחריך רישא רבא מלח שיבוטא

Amira of R Yosef: The amira of R Yosef follows the Gemara's kasha and is the first portion of the first lishna, quoted below.
> [גמ' השתא בשלוחו מקדש בו מיבעיא] אמר
> רב יוסף מצוה בו יותר מבשלוחו [כי הא דרב]

Ha d'Rav Safra: The section "ha d'Rav Safra" follows the amira of R Yosef, quoted below. You can read about the [[words of ha d'Rav Safra]]
> כי הא דרב [רב יוסף מצוה בו יותר מבשלוחו]
> ספרא מחריך רישא רבא מלח שיבוטא

Words of ha d'Rav Safra: The section "ha d'Rav Safra" includes the word ki, the word ha, the phrase d'Rav Safra, the word machrich, the word reisha, the word Rava, the word malach, and the word shibuta.

